  "bodyHtml": "<h2>Triage: who is this, and where are they going?</h2>\n<p>Not every resignation needs this playbook. Run it when the person had real access &mdash; to trade secrets, source code, pricing, customer relationships, or sensitive systems &mdash; and the destination raises questions. The risk is highest when the move is to a direct competitor, to a customer, or to a venture the person is starting. Decide the tier in the first hours; it sets how much of what follows you actually do.</p>\n<ul class=\"checklist\">\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"dep1\"><label for=\"dep1\"><strong>Pull every agreement the person signed.</strong> Offer letter, confidentiality/NDA, IP-assignment, non-compete, non-solicit (of customers and of employees), and any equity or bonus clawback terms. Find the executed versions, not the templates &mdash; what they actually signed is the only thing that matters.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"dep2\"><label for=\"dep2\"><strong>Read the covenants against current law before relying on them.</strong> Enforceability of non-competes varies sharply by state and is actively in flux; several states limit or ban them outright, and the standards keep moving. Non-solicits and confidentiality terms generally travel better, but not everywhere. Confirm against the current rule in the governing state before threatening anything.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"dep3\"><label for=\"dep3\"><strong>Confirm where they are going, and in what role.</strong> A lateral move to a non-competing function is a different problem from a same-territory sales role at a rival. Map the new role to the specific obligations it would implicate.</label></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Preserve before you touch anything</h2>\n<p>This is the phase that gets skipped under time pressure and cannot be recovered. The forensic window is short, and routine IT hygiene &mdash; reimaging, reassigning, wiping &mdash; destroys the best evidence you will ever have.</p>\n<ul class=\"checklist\">\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"dep4\"><label for=\"dep4\"><strong>Freeze the IT reissue process for this person immediately.</strong> One email to IT: do not wipe, reimage, reassign, or factory-reset the laptop, phone, or any account. Park the hardware; do not redeploy it.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"dep5\"><label for=\"dep5\"><strong>Forensically image the laptop, phone, and accounts.</strong> A defensible bit-for-bit image &mdash; ideally by a qualified examiner, with chain of custody &mdash; before anyone logs in to &ldquo;just check.&rdquo; Casual browsing alters metadata and access times you may later need. Limit this to company-owned devices and accounts; before imaging a personally-owned phone or device, or a personal account (see below), confirm ownership and your consent or policy authority, because imaging personal property or accounts carries its own legal exposure.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"dep6\"><label for=\"dep6\"><strong>Preserve the back-end logs, not just the device.</strong> Email, cloud storage, VPN, badge/door, code repositories, CRM, and DLP logs all live on the company side and age out on their own retention clocks. Identify them and hold them now.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"dep7\"><label for=\"dep7\"><strong>Capture personal-account touchpoints you can see.</strong> Note any personal email, cloud, or messaging accounts that appear in your logs. You cannot seize them, but knowing they exist shapes both the investigation and any later demand.</label></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Investigate the access</h2>\n<p>The question is narrow: in the final weeks, did this person move company information somewhere it should not be? Most of the answer lives in the artifacts you just preserved.</p>\n<ul class=\"checklist\">\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"dep8\"><label for=\"dep8\"><strong>Review downloads and file activity in the final weeks.</strong> Spikes in volume, bulk exports, and access to material outside the person&rsquo;s normal scope &mdash; the &ldquo;why was she pulling the whole customer list&rdquo; pattern.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"dep9\"><label for=\"dep9\"><strong>Check removable-media and USB history.</strong> External drives connected, what was copied, when. Often the cleanest single indicator of intent.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"dep10\"><label for=\"dep10\"><strong>Trace email-to-personal-account and forwarding.</strong> Messages and attachments sent to personal addresses, auto-forward rules, and large or unusual outbound attachments in the run-up to resignation.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"dep11\"><label for=\"dep11\"><strong>Look at cloud uploads and sync.</strong> Personal cloud drives, file-sharing links, and sync clients installed late in tenure. Movement off the managed perimeter is the thing to find.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"dep12\"><label for=\"dep12\"><strong>Keep the investigation channeled through counsel.</strong> Run the analysis so the work product and conclusions can be protected, and so findings are framed by someone who knows what is and isn&rsquo;t actionable. Privilege cannot be retrofitted after the fact.</label></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Manage access and secure the relationships</h2>\n<p>Two competing pressures: cut off access before anything else walks out, but not so abruptly that you tip off a person you are still quietly investigating. Plan the timing deliberately.</p>\n<ul class=\"checklist\">\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"dep13\"><label for=\"dep13\"><strong>Build a staged credential-disablement schedule.</strong> Map every system and pick a cutover time &mdash; commonly the end of the last working session. Too early tips your hand and may be premature if the person stays through a notice period; too late leaves the door open. Coordinate, don&rsquo;t improvise.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"dep14\"><label for=\"dep14\"><strong>Reset shared and service credentials the person knew.</strong> Shared logins, API keys, admin passwords, and anything they could still reach from outside. Individual accounts are only half the exposure.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"dep15\"><label for=\"dep15\"><strong>Plan the customer-transition message before the news spreads.</strong> Decide who owns each key account, who calls the customer, and what is said. A clean, prompt transition is itself a defense to claims of solicitation and disruption later.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"dep16\"><label for=\"dep16\"><strong>Reassign accounts and introduce the successor early.</strong> The longer a relationship sits &ldquo;belonging&rdquo; to a departed person, the easier it is to move. Visible continuity protects the relationship and the record.</label></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>The exit conversation and what follows</h2>\n<ul class=\"checklist\">\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"dep17\"><label for=\"dep17\"><strong>Use a written exit acknowledgment.</strong> A short document the person signs at departure, reminding them of continuing confidentiality, return-of-property obligations, and any non-solicit or non-compete terms &mdash; with the agreements attached. It removes the &ldquo;I didn&rsquo;t know I was still bound&rdquo; defense and confirms what was returned.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"dep18\"><label for=\"dep18\"><strong>Decide whether a reminder letter is warranted.</strong> Where the destination genuinely implicates the covenants, a measured letter to the departing employee &mdash; and sometimes to the new employer &mdash; restating the obligations can prevent a problem without litigation. Keep it factual; an overbroad or threatening letter where the covenant is weak invites a declaratory-judgment suit and bad optics.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"dep19\"><label for=\"dep19\"><strong>If misappropriation is suspected, issue a litigation hold and involve counsel now.</strong> Trade-secret matters move fast &mdash; injunctive relief is often the whole point &mdash; and spoliation by the company is an avoidable own-goal. See <a href=\"litigation-hold-checklist.html\">Litigation Hold: Trigger to Release</a>.</label></li>\n  <li class=\"check\"><input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"dep20\"><label for=\"dep20\"><strong>Mind the mirror image when you are the one hiring.</strong> The same diligence protects you when you are the new employer receiving someone else&rsquo;s departing employee &mdash; review their covenants, run a clean-hands onboarding, and enforce a do-not-bring-it-with-you rule. See <a href=\"hiring-from-competitor.html\">Hiring From a Competitor</a>.</label></li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"callout\">\n  <span class=\"callout-label\">The thing behind the thing</span>\n  <p>Image first, investigate second. A reissued or wiped laptop is destroyed evidence &mdash; and in most trade-secret cases the single most valuable proof of what left and why lives in the departing employee&rsquo;s own download history, USB log, and sent mail. Lose that, and you are litigating a hunch.</p>\n</div>",
